## .NET 8 Migration: `BackgroundProcessor`

### The Core Problem

`Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` **throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8**. `ThreadAbortException` will never be raised. This isn't just a deprecation — your `Stop()` method will crash and your graceful-abort cleanup path is dead code.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Replaces ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit cleanly — no ResetAbort equivalent needed
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2);

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cancellation (replaces _running = false + Abort)

        // Wait for graceful exit with a timeout
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't finish in time — log a warning.
            // There is no forced-kill equivalent in .NET 8. By design.
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **`Thread.Abort()` throws at runtime** | It compiles fine but throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. No compiler warning. |
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a synchronous `Socket.Read` or `Monitor.Wait`, `CancellationToken` won't interrupt it. You **must** migrate blocking I/O to async (`await ReadAsync(token)`). |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | `_running = false` can't wake a thread blocked inside a synchronous call. `CancellationToken` integrates with `async/await`, `SemaphoreSlim.WaitAsync`, channels, etc. |
| **No forced termination exists** | .NET 8 has no `Abort()` replacement. Design for cooperative cancellation. If third-party code can't be cancelled, isolate it in a separate **process** (not thread). |
| **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` is dead code** | It silently disappears — the rollback logic never runs. This is a **data-loss risk** if you port without rewriting the catch. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws** | Even if you keep the catch block "just in case," `ResetAbort()` will crash. |

### If You Must Keep Synchronous Code

Use `CancellationToken.Register` to unblock synchronous waits:

```csharp
// Example: unblock a ManualResetEventSlim
using var reg = token.Register(() => _waitHandle.Set());
_waitHandle.Wait(); // now gets unblocked on cancellation
```

### Migration Checklist

1. Replace `Thread` + `volatile bool` → `Task` + `CancellationTokenSource`
2. Replace `Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`
3. Replace `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException)`
4. Delete `Thread.ResetAbort()` — no equivalent needed
5. Convert blocking I/O to `async` variants that accept `CancellationToken`
6. Implement `IAsyncDisposable` to ensure cleanup
7. Search your codebase for any other `Thread.Abort` / `ResetAbort` calls — they **will** crash at runtime with zero compiler warnings
